article.description: Jerome James had a season-high 16 points and tied another season best with seven rebounds against Detroit's bruising front line, leading the SuperSonics to a 95-87 victory over the Pistons on Friday night.
article.headline: Detroit drops back-to-back games on the road
article.linkText: James, Sonics grit out victory over Pistons
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Whether it's defense, gritty hard fouls or the surprise scoring he showed against the defending NBA champions, Seattle center Jerome James believes he can give whatever's asked. James had a season-high 16 points and tied another season best with seven rebounds against Detroit's bruising front line, leading the SuperSonics to a 95-87 victory over the Pistons on Friday night. One of his best efforts ever? James was too modest to agree. "I can't really say. I don't focus on my own personal games," he said. "I focus on my ability to accommodate, to give the team what they need. ... Whatever the position calls for that night, I just want to go out and do it." James added three blocked shots, and the Sonics matched the intensity of the NBA's most physical team. Inside players Danny Fortson, Reggie Evans and Nick Collison were willing to bang with anybody in a blue jersey. "These are the types of games you'll be playing at this time of the season, where it's grind-it-out," Seattle coach Nate McMillan said. "You've got to make breaks for yourself and you've got to have good execution, good defense and you've got to play with heart." Rashard Lewis led the Sonics with 18 points, and Ray Allen and Luke Ridnour added 15 points each. With James leading the way inside, Seattle survived a tough night on the perimeter -- with Allen shooting 3-of-17 and Lewis 6-of-14. Since the All-Star break, James said opponents have been pinning Allen and Lewis when they come off of screens. That placed even more importance on finding offense from somewhere else. "Nobody's letting Ray or Rashard play," James explained. "They're jumping them really hard. So my whole focus tonight was, when those guys were getting trapped, to get open and run to the basket." The Pistons, who had their eight-game winning streak snapped Thursday night in Phoenix, hadn't lost consecutive game since a four-game losing streak from Jan. 18-24. Richard Hamilton led Detroit with 15 points and Chauncey Billups added 13. Ben Wallace scored 12 points and had 10 rebounds, and Rasheed Wallace finished with 10 points and 11 rebounds. The Pistons missed nine straight shots early in the fourth period. There were 13 ties and 12 lead changes through three periods, but Seattle's 11-4 burst helped build an 80-73 lead at the 6-minute mark. "We didn't match their energy and we got into foul trouble early in the fourth quarter," Detroit coach Larry Brown said. "Give them credit. They had a lot of guys step up and play well." Included in Seattle's run were four straight buckets. Fortson muscled for one, Allen drove for another and Lewis posted up Tayshaun Prince. Then Antonio Daniels drove the baseline, drew Ben Wallace's fourth foul and finished a three-point play. "We responded to the challenge to beat this team," McMillan said. After Hamilton completed a three-point play to trim Detroit's deficit to 82-76, Allen made a free throw and James hit a huge shot when he collected a loose ball and fired in an 8-footer to beat the shot clock with 2:57 to play. "That was a running hook," James said, laughing. "I had that one all the way. It would have been a lot more fluid if he hadn't grabbed me." Billups missed a layup at the other end, and Lewis extended Seattle's lead to 87-76 with a jumper from the left side. "It was a good game," Billups said. "We had our chances but they got loose balls and extra rebounds." Seattle's inside game was sure to be tested against Detroit's front court, but James got off to a great start -- missing only one of his first five attempts and blocking two shots in the opening period. He finished 8-of-10 from the floor and got a standing ovation when he left with 35.3 seconds to play. "Jerome has been good these last couple of games for us," McMillan said. "We're looking to give him the ball. He's taking his time and being patient and giving us a low-post presence."

Game notes
Sonics G Ronald "Flip" Murray didn't suit up because of a sinus infection. ... The Pistons reacquired C Elden Campbell, who was traded away in January and then waived by Utah and New Jersey. ... Former Seattle star Gus Williams, whose No. 1 jersey hangs from the KeyArena rafters, had a courtside seat on the baseline.
